<subSubSection id="C34F6548FFBCFFF7FF1DDAADFBDBF6E8" pageId="8" pageNumber="209" type="description">
<paragraph id="8BEA36C3FFBCFFF7FF1DDAADFBDBF6E8" blockId="8.[151,1437,223,502]" pageId="8" pageNumber="209">
Only two species are recognized in this genus, and both are known from 
<collectingCountry id="F3427653FFBCFFF7FC62DAADFA70F7E7" box="[1000,1072,223,249]" name="Brazil" pageId="8" pageNumber="209">Brazil</collectingCountry>
. They have the antennae 8-segmented, and segments III and IV bear a forked sense cone, IV and an additional long sense cone at the inner apical margin (
<figureCitation id="136E2A46FFBCFFF7FF7CDB55FF0BF65C" box="[246,331,295,322]" captionStart="FIGURES 34–51" captionStartId="20.[151,264,1780,1804]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,181,1757]" captionTargetId="figure-21@20.[151,1435,181,1757]" captionTargetPageId="20" captionText="FIGURES 34–51. Panchaetothripinae species. Antenna 34–47: (34) Arachisothrips millsi; (35) Brachyurothrips anomalus; (36) Bradinothrips williamsi; (37) Caliothrips cangaceiro sp. n.; (38) Caliothrips punctipennis; (39) Dinurothrips vezenyii; (40) Elixothrips brevisetis; (41) Heliothrips haemorrhoidalis; (42) Heliothrips longisensibilis; (43) Heliothrips similis; (44) Heliothrips zucchi; (45) Hoodothrips constrictus; (46) Hoodothrips lineatus; (47) Selenothrips rubrocinctus; (48) Brachyurothrips anomalus (head); (49) Caliothrips punctipennis (head and thorax); head and pronotum 50–51: (50) Caliothrips phaseoli; (51) Caliothrips nanus." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4397500" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4397500/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="209">Fig. 36</figureCitation>
). The head is reticulate only posteriorly, the pronotum has two pairs of long posteroangular setae, and the setal rows are incomplete on both fore wing veins. Described by 
<bibRefCitation id="EFC44B32FFBCFFF7FC4ADB39FA10F678" author="Hood, J. D." box="[960,1104,331,358]" pageId="8" pageNumber="209" pagination="205 - 212" refId="ref16832" refString="Hood, J. D. (1954) Three new Thysanoptera from Trinidad and British Guiana. Proceedings of the entomological Society of London B, 23, 205 - 212. https: // doi. org / 10.1111 / j. 1365 - 3113.1954. tb 00093. x" type="journal article" year="1954">Hood (1954)</bibRefCitation>
as a monotypic genus closely related to 
<taxonomicName id="4C554D40FFBCFFF7FE83DB1DFFC9F697" authorityName="Daniel" authorityYear="1904" box="[265,393,367,393]" class="Insecta" family="Thripidae" genus="Caliothrips" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="209" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B921EAD1FFBCFFF7FE83DB1DFFC9F697" box="[265,393,367,393]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="209">Caliothrips</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, in “ 
<taxonomicName id="4C554D40FFBCFFF7FE48DB1DFC02F697" authorityName="Haliday" authorityYear="1836" box="[450,578,367,393]" class="Insecta" family="Thripidae" genus="Heliothrips" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="209" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B921EAD1FFBCFFF7FE48DB1DFC02F697" box="[450,578,367,393]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="209">Heliothrips</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
-group”, but 
<bibRefCitation id="EFC44B32FFBCFFF7FD58DB1DFD35F694" author="Wilson, T. H." box="[722,885,367,394]" pageId="8" pageNumber="209" pagination="1 - 354" refId="ref18850" refString="Wilson, T. H. (1975) A monograph of the subfamily Panchaetothripinae (Thysanoptera: Thripidae). Memoirs of the American Entomological Institute, 23, 1 - 354." type="journal article" year="1975">Wilson (1975)</bibRefCitation>
included it in 
<taxonomicName id="4C554D40FFBCFFF7FB90DB1DFAC7F697" box="[1050,1159,367,393]" class="Insecta" family="Thripidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="209" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Thripinae">Thripinae</taxonomicName>
due to the presence of a mesothoracic spinula and long pronotal posteroangular setae. It is now placed in the 
<taxonomicName id="4C554D40FFBCFFF7FBCADBE1FB57F6B3" authorityName="Bagnall" authorityYear="1912" box="[1088,1303,403,429]" class="Insecta" family="Thripidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="209" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Panchaetothripinae">Panchaetothripinae</taxonomicName>
tribe 
<taxonomicName id="4C554D40FFBCFFF7FADCDBE1FEBFF6CF" class="Insecta" family="Thripidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="209" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Monilothripini">Monilothripini</taxonomicName>
after a phylogenetic analysis (
<bibRefCitation id="EFC44B32FFBCFFF7FDD9DBC5FD6DF6CC" author="Zhang, S. M. &amp; Mound, L. A. &amp; Feng, J. N." box="[595,813,439,466]" pageId="8" pageNumber="209" pagination="587 - 593" refId="ref19000" refString="Zhang, S. M., Mound, L. A. &amp; Feng, J. N. (2019 b) Sub-family relationships of Bradinothrips Hood and Parascolothrips Mound (Thysanoptera, Thripidae). Zootaxa, 4590 (5), 587 - 593. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 4590.5.6" type="journal article" year="2019">
Zhang 
<emphasis id="B921EAD1FFBCFFF7FD29DBCAFC94F6CF" box="[675,724,439,465]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="209">et al</emphasis>
. 2019b
</bibRefCitation>
). It shares with species of 
<taxonomicName id="4C554D40FFBCFFF7FBDBDBC5FAA3F6CF" authorityName="Moulton" authorityYear="1929" box="[1105,1251,439,465]" class="Insecta" family="Thripidae" genus="Monilothrips" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="209" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B921EAD1FFBCFFF7FBDBDBC5FAA3F6CF" box="[1105,1251,439,465]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="209">Monilothrips</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C554D40FFBCFFF7FA90DBC5FBDDF6CF" authorityName="Bhatti" authorityYear="1967" box="[1306,1437,439,465]" class="Insecta" family="Thripidae" genus="Zaniothrips" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="209" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B921EAD1FFBCFFF7FA90DBC5FBDDF6CF" box="[1306,1437,439,465]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="209">Zaniothrips</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
the presence of prominent setae on the pronotum and lack of sculpture on the ocellar triangle (
<bibRefCitation id="EFC44B32FFBCFFF7FB3FDBA9FBD0F6E8" author="Zhang, S. M. &amp; Mound, L. A. &amp; Feng, J. N." box="[1205,1424,475,502]" pageId="8" pageNumber="209" pagination="587 - 593" refId="ref19000" refString="Zhang, S. M., Mound, L. A. &amp; Feng, J. N. (2019 b) Sub-family relationships of Bradinothrips Hood and Parascolothrips Mound (Thysanoptera, Thripidae). Zootaxa, 4590 (5), 587 - 593. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 4590.5.6" type="journal article" year="2019">
Zhang 
<emphasis id="B921EAD1FFBCFFF7FA8CDBAEFB7EF6EB" box="[1286,1342,475,501]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="209">et al.</emphasis>
2019b
</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
